{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_irving_ver01/data/sn89060124/00415625820/1908030601/0043.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nFKKI). SASSCER. t, PTTO\nTERMS\u2014fl.oo per year. Single r\nv Q subscription discontinued until 11 m a.\npai.i unless at. the option I\" e I\u2019\" V, A' ~ker-\n\\I) VERT I SING KAlES\u2014Jran^i\ntiem *nts, #1 per inch tor tue tiret in.-\nrents for tlie second ami 45 cents\nnnent insertion. One mcli .1 sum. i?.\nm- ntlis 12 months, SB. Business\nexceeding 10 lines, *S P\" year \\S >en h-_. uni-\nHer of insertions is not marked m\nwill be continued until torbnl ami clis-ee' .k\n--cordingly. Yearly advertisers must oi.ht.e ad\nvertisemrnts to tl.e.r own business. Uu. an\nFigure Wo; k double pnoe.\ncents per line. Marriages and Deal I .nserti d\nfree' Obituaries and Personal Communications\n5 with this office should\nbe addressed. to \u201cThe Knquiueu.\nTHE PENNSYLVANIA KAJL\nUOAD\u2019S KEPOKT.\nThe sixty-first annual report of\nthe Pennsylvania Railroad Cora\npany bas been published, to which,\nunder the circumstances, exceptional\ninterest attaches. Gross trnllii\nearnings for 1907 on lines directly\noperated were $104,812,825, an in\ncrease of $16,572,943 over 1906.\nOp crating expenses, including\ntaxes, were $123,586,512, an increase\nof $18,065,834. Net earnings from\noperation 1 decreased, $1,492,891.\nTaking account of other income, in\nterest from investments, etc., and\nrents and interest paid, the com\npary\u2019s net income for the 3\u2019car was\n$33,575,056, a decrease of $2.099 244\nRecent Federal and State legisla\ntion is cited by President McCiea as\none of the principal causes of the\nfinancial panic and the diminished\nnet earnings. Prosperity, says the\nreport, had a \u201csevere cheek\u2019 in last\nNovember, which is now a fleeting\nrevenues. While a number of causes\nseriously disturbed public confidence\nand brought on the financial panic\nwhich bas so sharply aflectcd the\nbusiness interests of the country, an\nimportant one undoubtedly was the\nfear that as the result of recent Fed\neral and State legislation, the regu\nlation of the railways had approach\ned so nearly to an effort to control\ntheir management and revenues that\ninvestments therein were not assured\nof that protection to which they are\nentjiled. Eventually, it may be as\nsumed, questions that arise will be\nfairly adjusted, but in the meantime\nthe railways have to face the loss of\nrevenue consi quent upon the en\nforced idleness of their equipment,\nwhile to a number of employes this\nbas brought about either loss of em\nployment or reduction of hours of\nlabor.\u201d Lower passenger rales, ;l\nis shown, have not stimulated tmaci\nenough to offset the loss of revenue\nand the higher cost of operation, due\nto increases in wages and\ncost of operation. The cost per\npassenger per mile has increased\nnearly 13 per cent, and the cost per\ntrain mile nearlyT7 per cent., caus\ning a reduction of nearly 82 per\ncent, in the net earnings per passen\nger-train mile. Expenses have uni\nformly increased, while net earnings\nhave largely decreased. Till De\ncember there was a heavy increase\nin volume of freight traffic, tenage\nand t ton mileage showing a large\ngain, but a material reduction in\ngross and net earnings per ton per\nmile. The New York tunnel and\nterminal station will be completed, it\nis expected, in 1910 \u2014Baltimore Sun.\nTHE HOPKINS PROFESSOR\nSHIP OF EDUCATION.\nThe new professorship of education\nestablished in the Johns Hopkins\nUniversity indicates a purpose on\nthe part of the trustees of that pro\ngressive institution to render still\ncloser its relations with the agencies\nof primary, secondary and collegiate\neducation in Maryland says the\nBaltimore \u201cSun.\u201d It. is in effect a\nwidening of the field of work, winch\nis likely to benfit both the university\nand the schools. Pedagogy is an art\nof the utmost importance. The best\nteachers are perhaps born, not made.\nBut even a' born teacher will im\nprove bis efficiency by becoming\nacquainted with the best methods of\nteaching envolved in this and other\ncountries and ages, and the ordinary\nteacher, to whom good method is\nindispensable, will be vastly' benefit\ned by the guidance of the new chair\nof education.\nTime was when everybody was\nsupposed to be able to teach what he\nknew\u2014or, for that matter, what Ik\ndidn\u2019t know. There was no art or\nscience of teaching but every teach\ner stumbled along as best he could,\nto the injury often of the youthful\nminds. The absence of training fo.\nthe teacher and want of broad con\nprehension of aims and method:\ncaused an infinite waste of money,\ntime and energy. But \u201cwe luw\nchanged all that.\u201d\u2014At present\neducation is a science and pedagogy I\na well developed branch of it. i\nHopkins and the public are to hr\ncongratulated on the practical re-\ncognition of this fact in the uni ve li\nly\u2019s curriculum.\nCol A. E. Randall, president of ti e j\nUnited Stales Realty Company, has j\noffered to put up a new courthouse i\nfree for Prince George's county if the\ncounty scat is moved from Upper;\nMarlboro\u2019 to Buena ila.\nj\nOhio Republicans have nominated\na State ticket, adopted a platform\ngoing into national issues and nam-\ned delegates to the Chicago conven- 1 t\ntion instructed to vote for Taft \u201cua- i\ntil nominated.\u201d\nTHE PRINCE GEORGE\u2019S ENQUIRER\u2014PITER MARLBOROUGH. MARYLAND. MARCH 6, 1908\nOUK WASHINGTON LETTER\nWashington, 1). C. Feb 29, 190\nMu, Editor:\u2014 The purpose of the\nHearst League, or the Independence\nLeague as it prefers to be called, is\nstill the occasion of some anxiety and\ns.um; curiosity to Democratic leaders in\nWashington. They are at a loss to un\nderstand Mr. Hearsl\u2019s purpose in spend\ning untold sums of money to promote\nthis movement in national politics. At\none lime they thought they had found\nthe solution in the theory that Mr.\nHearst purposed to hold his convention\nafter the Republican and before the\nDemocratic national conventions and\nto endorse himself for President with\nthe purpose of opposing Mr. Bryan at\nDenver. It is now officially announced,\nhowever, that the Independence League\nConvention will follow the national\nconventions of both of the other parties\nand the political prognosticators in the\nnational capital are once more at sea.\nThere has been a rumor in circulation\nhere to the effect that it was the pur\npose of Mr. Hearst to have his League\nendorse Theodore Roosevelt for Presi\ndent, irrespective of what action might\nbe taken by the other conventions, and\nthis rumor is no more welcome to the\nRepublicans than to the Democrats.\nThose who maintain that this is the real\nintent of the Hearst organization say\nthat he believes that by nominating Mr.\nRoosevelt his party can poll a vote so\nlarge as to make it a central figure in\nall future national equations, even\nthough nothing else is accomplished\nthis year, and in support of their theory\nthev point t<> the fact that recent edi\ntu: T.s in the Hearst newspapers have\nbeen far more flattering to Mr. Roose\nvelt than ever before, and that from\ncondemnation they have changed to\npraise. Of course no such action could\nbe taken if Mr. Roosevelt could help it,\nas he particularly abhors Mr. Hears!,\nand has always refrained from inviting\nhim to the White House, even when he\nwas a member of Congresa, while the\nspeech of Secretary Root, which was\nlargely inspired by the President, was\nprobably the most potent factor in pre\nventing Mr. Hearst from defeating Mr.\nHughes in the race for the governorship\nof New York,\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s intense feeling\nagainst Mr. Hearst dates back to the\ntime when, as Governor of New York,\nMr. Roosevelt felt constrained to refuse\na pardon to a woman who had,been sen\ntenced to death for a most revolting\nmurder. Numerous frenzied appeals\nfor pardon had been forwarded to Gov\nernor Roosevelt and he had appointed\na commission of eminent jurors to in\nvestigate the case and advise him. The\ncommission advised that a pardon\nwould be a defeat of justice and he\nabided by its decision. The Hearst\nnewspapers were leading the propagan\nda for a pardon and when the Governor\nrefused they printed lurid editorials in\nwhich they said, among other things,\nthat it would be their unchanging pur\npose to prevent Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s wife\naud children from ever forgetting that\ntheir husband and father was a \u201cmur\nderer of women\u201d. Mr. Roosevelt never\nforgave the reference t\u00a9 his wife and\nfamily.\nThere is a peculiar situation In the\nSenate committee on Military Affairs.\nWhen the final vote on Brownsville was\ntaken this week, only two members had\nthe courage to vote for a resolution de\nclaring that it was their conviction that\nthe negro soldiers of the 35th Infantry\ndid not shoot up the town of Browns\nville. These were Foraker and Bulke\nley, both of whom arc intense haters of\nthe present administration. Now, how\never. some of the Republicans who vot\ned as they thought, saying that the evi\ndence showed that the negroes did the\nshooting, are hearing from the negro\nvoters in their states and they are be\ncoming scared. One of them, Senator\nWarner of Missouri, who practically\nconducted the prosecution and examin\ned the negro witnesses, as well as the\nwhite ones, has decided to introduce a\nbill providing that the President may\nrestore to the army and give back pay\nto any negro soldier who can prove bis\nentire innocence of having had a part\nin the assault, to the satisfaction of the\nWar Department. This is, of course, a\nfar better measure than the Foraker bill\nwhich provide? that the President must\nrestore all the discharged negroes, inno\ncent and guilty alike, but then Mr.\nForaker r.anwf perfectly well that bis\nbill wii, never pass, will never even be\nreported from the committee, and he is\nmerely seeking to vent his spleen\nagainst Roosevelt and Taft. Incident\nally, the fact that the Republican State\nconvention of Missouri, which instruct\ned its delegates for Taft, elected four\nnegroes as alternates to the convention\nmay have also been the result of Mr.\nWarner\u2019s anxiety.\nSenator Owen, of Oklahoma made a\nsplendid impression in the Senate this\nWeek when he debated the A Idrich bill,\nwhich, by the way, will probably be\npassed by the Senate next week. Mr.\nOwen exhibited a perfect command of\nlanguage and a fine presence when he\nmade his maiden speech. Later, how\never, he unfortunately advocated an\namendment to the Indian Appropria\ntion bill which would operate to re\nmove all the restrictions which Con\ngress has placed around the transfer of\nhis lands by the Indian, legislation bas\ned on the idea that the Indian is not\nyet competent to deal with white men\naud part bloods without getting cheat\ned., Mr. Owen too* the ground that\ninasmuch as the Indians of the Five\nCivilized Tii had been absorbed by\nthe t\u2022\u2022*.: of Oklahoma, they were ne\nlonger .Indians, but citizens of the\ni United States. The unfortunate fea\n.ate of the affair was that Senator\n1 Given has secured options on abaut\n:J, \u2022J' 1 acres of the finest land i n Okla\nhoma which he is seeking to purchase\n1 f.-oro the Indians at prices which the\nSecretary of the Interior maintains are\nmerely nomina 1. Under these circum\nstances, the Senator lost in one day all\nthe ground he had gained in the Senate\non the day previous.\nThe President has sent to the Senate\nthirteen treaties framed at the Hague j\nconvention Eleven of them, it is said, j\nwi 1 be ratified without objection, but\ntwo wili mset with strong Democratic t\nopposition, and possibly with opposi- j\ntion from the majority. The two which\nare found objectionable are that deal- i\ning with prize courts and that practical\nly enunciating the Drago doctrine. 1\nOrder of P ublication\nWASHINGTON and POTOMAC\nSTEAMBOAT COMPANY, a corpora- i\ntion, Plaintiff.\nvs.\nFERNANDO TAYLOR, Defendant.\nIn the Circuit Court for Prince Geor\nge\u2019s County, Maryland, in Equity.\nNo. 3502 Equity\nTHE object of this suit is to vacate\naud set aside a tax deed from\nGeorge W. Hardy, Treasurer of Prince\nGeorge\u2019s Ceunly, to the defendant Fer-\nnand\u00a9 Taylor, dated April 9th, 1907,\nrecorded among the Laud Records of\nsaid County, in Liber No. 39, at folio\n527 thereof; and to vacate and set aside\na tax sale, and the confirmation there\nof by the said Court of the property\ndescribed in said tax deed, being cer\ntain real estate and improvements there\non situate in Prince Georges County,\nMaryland, containing 249 acres called\nin said dee I aud tax sale \u201cSimpson\nPlace,\u201d and commonly known as\n\u2022\u2018River View;\u201d and to remove the cloud\nJpon the title of the plaintiff in and to\nsaid land, and premises by the record\nof said tax deed; and to enjoin the de\nfendant from setting up any claim to\nsaid land and premises; and to have an\naccount stated of the taxes, interests,\npenalties, and costs which may be due\nfrom said land and premises.\nThe bill states the above facts; and\nalso that the plaintiff is a corporation\nand the owner in fee simple of said\nproperty under a deed from \u201cE. S.\nRandall Steamboat and Excursion\nCompany,\u201d a corporation, dated May 4,\n1906, and recorded among said land re\ncords in Liber No. 28, at folio 330 there\nof, on June 1, 19J6; that said \u201cE. S-\nRandall Steamboat and Excursion\nCom\u00dfany\u201d was the owner in fee simple\nof said property under a deed from\nEphraim S. Randall and wife dated Ju\nly 12, 1900 and recorded among the said\nland records in Liber J. B- 11, at folio\n389 thereof; that said plaintiff ie now\nand it and those under whom it claims\nhave been fer more than twenty years,\nin the undisturbed, peaceable, exclusive\nadverse and continuous possession of\nthe whole ef said land; that said laud is\nsituate upon the Potomac River, and\nfor the last twenty years has been call\ned \u201cRiver View,\u201d and used as a summer\nresort by plaintiff and those under\nwhom it claims; that the said defendant\nFernando Taylor, claims title t\u00a9 said\nland and premises by virtue of said tax\ndeed, and a tax sale thereof made in\nMarch 1995, for county and State taxes\nfor the year 1904. which sale was re\nported to said Court on April 1, 1905,\nand finally ratified by said Court on\nMarch 31, 1907; that said tax sale was\nimproperly made and void; that said\nfinal ratification was improvidently and\nimproperly passed, that said tax deed\nis void because never properly scaled\nby the grantor therein; tnat plaintiff on\nOctober 12, 1907, tendered the full\namount of taxes, interest, penalties and\ncosts to dat\u00a9 of said tender, to the said\nTreasurer, and the same was refused by\nhim; and that said Fernando Taylor\nis a non-resident \u00a9f the State of Mary\nland.\nIT IS THEREFORE THIS third day\n\u2022f March, 1908, ordered by the Circuit\nCourt for Prince George\u2019s County, sit\nting in Equity, that the plaintiff, by\ncausing a copy of this order to be in\nserted in a newspaper published in\nPrinc\u00a9 George\u2019s County, Maryland,\nonce a week for four successive weeks,\nbefore the fourth day of April, A. D.\n1908, give notice to the said absent de\nfendant; Fernando Taylor, of the ob\nject and substance of this bill, warning\nhim to appear in this Court in person\nor by attorney on or before the first\nday \u00a9f May next, to show cause, if any\nhe have, why a decree ought not to be\npassed as prayed.\nGEORGE C. MERRICK, A. J.\nTrue Copy\u2014Test:\nBENJ. D. STEPHEN, Clerk\nof Circuit Court for Prince George\u2019s\nCounty, Md.\nMrb64t.\nM ORTGAQEE\u2019S SaLE\n\u2014OF\u2014\nV aluablelmproved Real\nEstate\nAT CAPITOL HEIGHTS, PRINCE\nGEORGE\u2019S COUNTY, MARY\nLAND.\nUNDER and by Virtue of the Powers\nof Sale contained in a Mortgage\nfrom Henrietta J. Sweeney.and husband\nto O. B- Zantiinger, dated May sth,\n1905, and duly recorded among the\nLand Records of Princ\u00a9 George\u2019s Coun\nty in Liber No 23 folio 554 et. seq., de\nfault having been made in the cove\nnants \u00a9f said Mortgage, the undersign\ned will offer for sal\u00a9 on\nMONDAY, MARCH 31th, 1908.\nAt 5 o\u2019clock P. M.\nat public auction on the premises, all\nthe property in said Mortgage describ\ned, to-wit Lots numbered Thirty-one\nThirty-two, Thirty-three, Thirty-four,\nThirty-flye, Thirty-six, Thirty-seven,\nThirty-eight, Thirty-nine, Forty, Forty\none, Forty-two, Forty-three, Forty\nfour, Forty-five, Forty-six and Forty\nseven, in Block numbered Forty-one,\nin the Subdivision known as Capitol\nHeights, as per plat of same duly re\ncorded among the Land Records of\nsaid County. Improved by six room\ndwelling bouse and cellar under entire\nbouse. Stable for 12 horses and d cows\nLarge wagon and carriage shed. Well\non the property. This property is most\nadmirably located and about 10 minutes\nwalk from Electric car line.\nTERMS OF SALE:\nOne-third Cash upon the ratification\nof the sale by the Court. Balance in\nsix and twelve months from the day of\nsale. Deterred payments to bear six\nper cent interest per annum from the\nday of sale and to be secured to tbe sat\nisfaction of the undersigned. Acknr w\nladgment, recording and conveyancing\nat cost of purchaser. A cash deposit\nof S2OO will be required on day of ?.le.\nO- B. ZANTZINGER, Mortgages.\n908 G. St N. W.,\nWashington, D. C.\nWells, Hoover. Clagott and Wells,\nSolicitors\nCommercial Bank Bld\u2019g Washington,\nD. C.\nMrhOts.\nOrder of Ratification.\nALEXANDER T. LEFTWICH, Ad\nministrator.\nvs.\nFANNY C. HAIRSTON, et al\nIn the Circuit Court for Prince George\u2019s j\nC\u00a9uuty in Equity.\nNo 1699 Equity.\nORDERED, This 3rd day of March\n1908 that the Auditor\u2019s Report and\nj Account B filed in this cause be ratifi\n-1 ed and confirmed unless cause to the\nj contrary be shown on or before tbe 21st\nday of March 1908, provided a copy of\nthis order be inserted in some news\npaper published in Prince George's\nCounty once in each of two successive\nweeks before the said 21st day of March\n1908.\nBENJ. D. STEPHEN, Clerk.\nTrue Copy Test:\nBENJ. D. STEPHEN, Clerk.\nMh74t 1\nN OTIC TO\nrjVHIS IS TO GIVE NOTICE. That\nX the undersigned lias obtained from\nthe Orphans\u2019 Court of Prince George s\ncounty, letters of admiai.-triitioii upon\nthe personal estate ol\nenocii g. perrie,\nlate of Prince Geonre\u2019s county, deceas\ned. All persons having claims against\nsaid deceased are hereby warned u> ex-\nhibit the same, with the vouchers there-\non legally authenticated on or be for\nthe 18th day of Aug 190 S; or they may\notherwise by law be exclu led lro;n ab\nbenefit of said estate. AH per ons in\ndebted to said estate are requested to\nmake immediate payment. Given uu- I\nder my baud this ISlli day of February,\n1908.\nHOWARD M. PERRIE,\nAdministrator of Enoch G. Pcrnc, de\nceased.\nFeblSlm.\nOrder of Ratification\nWILLIAM MEYER LEU IN, Surviv\ning Trustee.\nVS.\nJESSE D. GIBBS AND FLORENCE\nB. GIBBS, his wife.\nIn the Circuit Court for Prince George\u2019s\nCounty in Equity.\nNo. 34G1 Equity.\nORDERED >n this 12th day of Feb\nruary, 1908, by tb e Circuit Court\nor Prince George\u2019s County in Equity,\nhat the sale of the property mentioned\nn these proceedings made and reported\ny William Meyer Lewin, Trustee, be\nalified aud confirmed unless cause to\nhe contrary thereof be shown ou or\nbefore the 7th day of March next, pro\nvided a copy of this order be inserted in\nsome newspaper published in Prince\nGeorge\u2019s Count}\u2019, Maryland, once in\neach of three successive weeks before\nthe 7th day of March next.\nThe report stales the am unt of sale\nto be S2OO\nD. STEPHEN, Clerk\nTrue Copy Test:\nBENJ. D. STEPHEN, Clerk.\nFebl44t.\nN otice to Creditors.\nTHIS IS to give notice. That the un\ndersigned has obtained from tue\nOrphans\u2019 Court of Prince George\u2019s\nCounty letters testamentary upon\nthe personal estate of\nJAMES W. GILLINGHAM,\nlate of Prince George\u2019s county, deceas\ned. All persons having claims against\nsaid deceased are hereby w rued to ex\nhibit the same, with the vouchers there\non legally authenticated before the 7th\nday of Aug- 1908; or they may other\nwise by law be excluded from all bene\nfit of said estate. Ail p rsons imlebt\ned to said estate are requested to make\nimmediate payment. Givu under\nhand this 6th day of February, 1 *OB.\nSAMUEL W. GILLIXGL A..M,\nWILLIAM M. GILLINGHAM.\nAdministrators of James W. Gilling\nham, deceased-\nFeb7lm.\nW ANTED.\nAN OLD MAHOGANY Four Post\nBedstead in good condition. Any\none having one for sale at a reasonable\nprice address this office and party\u2019s\nname.\nFeb7.\nNOTICE.\nBY MUTUAL AGREEMENT\nWYVILL BROTHERS,\nContractors and Builders\nHAVE DISSOLVED partnership; but\nwill not bid in opposition to one anoth\ner. Persons wishing work done in their\nline will please notify any one of the\nthree parties.\nA. J. WTVILL. W.M. n. WYTILI\nM. J. WTVILL.\nJanlltc UPPER MARLBORO\u2019, MD.\nAttractive Priming\nAT\nGOST 1\nIS WHAT YOU GET FROM\nTHE JOB OFFICE\nOF THE\nPrince George\u2019s Enquirer\nENVELOPES.\nNOTE PA PER,\nBILL HEADS,\nSptctui Pi ice.\nPOSTER WORK.\nPAMPHLETS.\nFOLDERS.\nCIRCU LAPS.\nDODGERS.\nAnything in the print!:.g line can be\nhad promptly any eiay in the week.\nA trial order solicited\nC P. Phone.\nThe Prince George\u2019s Enquirer\nUPPER MAftLBOR(V, MD.\ni IS 1\nFIRST NATIONAL DANK\n\u2014OF\nSouthern Maryland\nj CAPITAL $25,000. SURPI US $!2 500.\nI\nWe want you to op n ai acc-i\nI with us. No matter how small,\nj Come to our Cashier an i la- v. .11\ni furnish the book of papers.\nIn these times no in: can r,\nituy precaution to keep bis ae.-oui.ts\nstraight and to take care of h's le\nceipls.\nWe do all your bo- k keeping free\nof cost.\nDon\u2019t Keep Cue Dollar idle.\nStart a Savings Acc unt for yc-ir\